                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d551">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5045/200: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-09-01T16:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 1, 1925—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 1—12:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>278. Department’s 282, August 31, 8 p.m. was read to Foreign Office whereupon
                    Embassy was informally advised that British Chargé d’Affaires at Peking would be
                    instructed to cooperate with his American colleague: First, in arranging
                    McEuen’s immediate suspension; second, in endeavoring to obtain as satisfactory
                    assurances as possible that McEuen will be retired in the event of his
                    vindication; and third, in expediting the holding of the judicial inquiry.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Houghton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
